An Act relative to abusive practices to change sexual orientation and gender identity.
Be it enacted by the Senate and House of Representatives in General Court assembled, and by the authority
of the same, as follows:
1 MA general law c.12 § 11I 1/2, which states under (b) "Access to reproductive health
2 care services and gender-affirming health care services is a right secured by the constitution and
3 laws of the commonwealth. Interference with this right, whether or not under the color of law, is
4 against the public policy of the commonwealth." With "gender-affirming health care services"
5 defined in (a) as "all supplies, care and services of a medical, behavioral health, mental health,
6 surgical, psychiatric, therapeutic, diagnostic, preventative, rehabilitative or supportive nature
7 relating to the treatment of gender dysphoria.
8 Purpose: This act is meant to adjust the practice of providing gender change healthcare
9 and sex trait modification to minors and provide proper preparation for any adult seeking sex
10 trait modification.
11 Chapter 112 of the General Laws is hereby amended by adding the following section:-
1 of 4

12 Section 275. (a) As used in this section, the following words shall, unless the context
13 clearly requires otherwise, have the following meanings:-
14 “Sexual orientation and gender identity change efforts”, any practice by a health care
15 provider that attempts or purports to impose change of an individual’s sexual orientation or
16 gender identity including, but not limited to, efforts to change behaviors or gender expressions or
17 to eliminate or reduce sexual or romantic attractions or feelings toward individuals of the same
18 sex; provided, however, that “sexual orientation and gender identity change efforts” shall not
19 include practices that: (i) (A) provide acceptance, support and understanding of an individual's
20 sexual orientation, gender identity, gender expression, or biological sex recognized at birth; (B)
21 facilitate an individual’s coping, social support and identity exploration and development; or (C)
22 are sexual orientation-neutral or gender identity-neutral, including interventions to prevent or
23 address unlawful conduct or unsafe sexual practices; and (ii) do not attempt or purport to impose
24 change of an individual's sexual orientation, gender identity, or biological sex recognized at
25 birth.
26 "Sex trait modification", all medical practices of a hormonal, pharmaceutical, or surgical
27 nature which seek to mimic or alter the appearance, function, or presence of primary and
28 secondary sexual characteristics in effort to ameliorate gender dysphoria, gender incongruence,
29 or any other gender identity-related distress.
30 (b) A health care provider shall identify and provide proper health care in line with the
31 biological sex of a patient. If the patient is under the age of 18, or 18 and still enrolled in
32 secondary school, healthcare providers shall engage with parents to determine the source of any
33 gender dysphoria and partner with any additional medical professionals to ensure the patient is
2 of 4

34 able to successfully navigate puberty and progress through the age of maturation based only on
35 the biological sex recognized at birth.
36 (b)(1) Health Insurance providers covering an individual who is listed as a minor family
37 member of a policy holder, shall not provide sexual orientation and gender identity change
38 efforts coverage except in the mental health of the patient to navigate puberty and achieve
39 adulthood based only on the biological sex recognized at birth.
40 (b)(2) Healthcare providers shall provide all documentation relating to medications and
41 course of treatment, including. but not limited to, side effects and length of time a patient who is
42 seeking sexual orientation and gender identity change services will be required to take
43 medication and the cost of those medications for the entirety of the course of treatment/therapy.
44 (b)(3) No sexual orientation and gender identity change medical procedures aimed at
45 altering sex or gender that involve surgical interventions or the use of medication (i.e. hormone
46 therapy, puberty blockers, et al.) shall be administered to any patient under the age of 19 that is
47 still enrolled in secondary school, however patients 18 years and older, having graduated from
48 secondary school, seeking sexual orientation and gender identity change medical procedures and
49 interventions must utilize mental health therapy for a minimum of 6 months from initial request
50 for sexual orientation and gender identity change intervention. Additionally, no surgical
51 procedure shall be performed on any person 18 years or older, that are no longer enrolled in
52 secondary school, seeking sexual orientation and gender identity change therapy unless they
53 utilize mental health therapy for a minimum of 12 months from initial request for sexual
54 orientation and gender identity change surgery.
3 of 4

55 (b)(4) Healthcare insurers shall not be required to cover medication or surgical
56 procedures for sexual orientation and gender identity change therapy.
57 (c) Enforcement:
58 (c)(1) Any healthcare provider determined by a court of law to have violated the above
59 act shall be fined a minimum $10,000.00 for the first offense and each violation thereafter.
60 (c)(2) If a second offense occurs, as determined by a court of law, healthcare providers
61 shall surrender their license to practice to the appropriate governing body for a minimum of 5
62 (five) years.
63 (c)(3) A third offense shall terminate a healthcare provider's license permanently and a
64 minimum 5 year sentence to prison will be imposed.
